history-civil rights, rock and roll, television, and the emergence of a youth culture-as he tells how white families around American Bandstand's studio mobilized to maintain all-white neighborhoods and how local school officials reinforced segregation long after Brown vs. Board of Education. The Nicest Kids in Town powerfully illustrates how national issues and history have their roots in local situations, and how nostalgic representations of the past, like the musical film Hairspray, based on the American Bandstand era, can work as impediments to progress in the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryx20th centuryxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights movementsxHistoryx20th centuryxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aCivil rights movementszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMinorities on television. 0aSegregationxHistoryx20th centuryxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aSegregationzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951600423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520951600.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles